**Failure to find com.capitalone.dashboard:core:jar:2.0.5-SNAPSHOT when compiling the Jenkins module**

mvn 3.5.4 + java 1.8 + Centos 7

Have done git clone of the repo, cd hygieia-jenkins. Trying to build the Jenkins module independently.

[ERROR] Failed to execute goal on project hygieia-publisher: Could not resolve dependencies for project org.jenkins-ci.plugins:hygieia-publisher:hpi:2.0.5-SNAPSHOT: Failure to find com.capitalone.dashboard:core:jar:2.0.5-SNAPSHOT in http://repo.jenkins-ci.org/public/ was cached in the local repository, resolution will not be reattempted until the update interval of repo.jenkins-ci.org has elapsed or updates are forced -> [Help 1]

The pom.xml file requires 2.0.5-SNAPSHOT for core and hpi elements. `mvn test -X` shows that the 2.0.5 version of the artefact doesn't seem to exist on jenkins-ci.

column11:
419065437 @stphnwallace : Please do the following again:

1. Remove the existing repository.
2. Do a fresh git clone of the hygieia repository again to get the latest copy.
3. Then cd into "core" and do "mvn clean install". This will install the core jar into your local repository.
4. And then cd into "hygieia-jenkins-plugin", and do "mvn clean install" or "mvn clean package". Thanks ! subodhbattina

But the problem is the fact your are telling spring to look for prefix ‘git’ within the properties file with ‘--spring.config.name=git‘  but all the ‘git.’ Settings are commented out.

column2:
Issues:

both variables hostUrl & apiUrl are essentially from what I can see used in slightly different ways when they can be used exchangeably. Also found that the following use case would cause interesting errors because of how we are appending and reconstructing the apiUrl.

Given provided bitbucket host: https://some.bitbucket.server.com:8443/ 

Note: This is an internal only used server, and its listening on that specific port as is the case.

The apiUrl would result in the following.

https://some.bitbucket.server.com/rest/api/1.0/8443/projects/****/repos/****

Obviously this will result in a 404 error because your logic doesn't cater for a port being appended to the url string.

On my own personal repo I've modified this to declare this abstraction the same way you've done the rest.

```
url = new URL(repoUrl);
hostName = url.getHost();
protocol = url.getProtocol();
port = url.getPort();

String hostUrl = protocol + "://" + hostName + ":" + port;
```

Also needed to modify the substring length with +1

`String repoName = repoUrl.substring(hostUrl.length() + 1, repoUrl.length());
`

I also found bugs with the authorization header in the api call when running the makeRestCall function. I found the logic assume that decryptedPassword will originate from a encrypted password, however in my local instance I'm not encrypting my password in the UI, and therefore it will crash and leave my decryptedPassword as blank resulting in a 401 when querying the bitbucket server.

I think the problem here is the assumption all passwords will follow suit by being encrypted and forcing a decryption on that variable which is not the case. I've modified the code locally to work, however can this also be looked into and resolved?

I am also open to discussing many more things I've found that can be improved / enhanced in the repo, some being problematic in my opinion that would be higher priority, if you could DM I'll communicate further in private.

column2:
Issues:

> MONGODB_HOST=`echo $MONGO_PORT|sed 's;.*://\([^:]*\):\(.*\);\1;'`

> MONGODB_PORT=`echo $MONGO_PORT|sed 's;.*://\([^:]*\):\(.*\);\2;'`

This will result in db connection 27017:27017 which is therefore incorrect. Following the docker-compose file format it should be db:27017, therefore it needs to be changed to the following.


> MONGODB_HOST=`echo $MONGO_HOST|sed 's;.*://\([^:]*\):\(.*\);\1;'`

> MONGODB_PORT=`echo $MONGO_PORT|sed 's;.*://\([^:]*\):\(.*\);\2;'`

Also found multiple issues in regards to syntax & consistency, I see variables everywhere referencing MONGODB_HOST, then I'll see MONGO_HOST - this feels very redundant.

Also the lack of double quote to prevent globbing and word splitting, when referencing variables among other things.
column5: properties-builder.sh
column11:
409947494 @xUnholy Please submit a PR if you find a fix to this problem. rvema
413597120 @xUnholy - the properties-build.sh files definitely need work. The pattern we want to move to is similar to this one: https://github.com/Hygieia/ExecDashboard/blob/master/exec-ui/docker-util/docker-entrypoint.sh so we don't need `&&` in our CMD. That being said the example you gave for the MONGODB_HOST and MONGODB_PORT is actually correct. It's hard to read I know but if you look closely there are two capture groups in the regex. MONGODB_HOST becomes the first capture group and MONGODB_PORT becomes the second. We want to revamp all of this and would love to hear your thoughts and would be more than happy to work with you to improve this. matthewbeasley
416395602 @matthewbeasley 

I haven't had too much time to review the Hygieia - we did a product analysis and decided we would just stay with our current prometheus / grafana stack for monitoring, however I can see Hygieia being much better once there is some more maturity in the product.

I would suggest that the issue I've raised here is also perhaps not the best way to handle it, however if you want I can spend some time looking into some of these small things and raise a PR for you guys to decide on if you'd like? 

I also raised another ticket the same day as this one which doesn't have any current comments as of yet.

Regards,

Michael.  xUnholy
456243046 The `mongo_port` also threw me for a bit. Key is that the scheme should be included like

```
MONGO_PORT=tcp://hostname:27017
```

Without the `:` in the scheme, the `sed` command groups don't work out and you get `27017:27017` like @xUnholy mentions.

Honestly, I would find it better if we just uniformly used the environmetn variables `MONGODB_HOST` and `MONGODB_PORT`. spyoungtech
458811010 This has been fixed as part of PR #2694 . Please retrieve the latest code and retry. Do reopen if you run into this issue. rvema

422064316 @baitiandi : 
1. Can you please share the values you are using to create the widget?
2. Please open the developer console on your browser, and please share any errors you may be seeing on the console at the point you create the widget.
3. Also, in your MongoDB repository, Run these queries below to check the if the repo url is saved in its entirety:

3.1 Run the below query on "collectors" collection. Make a note of the "_id" value from the result on the query below
**{ "name": "Bitbucket" }**
3.2 Run the below query on "collector_items" collection. 
Put in the repo url you have, and the collector id value from the above query.
See you get back any data.
{ "collectorId": ObjectId("<collector id value>"), $and: [ { "options.url": "<repo url>" } ] }

First lets make sure you have this data, and then go from there.
Please do share the logs, both from the browser console and the api logs. Thanks !

column5: Hygieia-UI images does not work
column11:
410048121 Hello,

I am facing similar issues with my own platform. From what I saw there are too use cases (maybe more):

- easiest one : the host network is down/unavailable : the mapping does not seem to occur when the Nginx proxy cannot reach the API (sanity check), which stops the UI
=> you can change the proxy setup to avoid this blocking check like this (Nginx tip found elsewhere):
```
location /api {
set $apiurl http://API_HOST:API_PORT/api;
proxy_pass   $apiurl;
}
```
It does not ensure that the connectivity works but your UI should start.


- hardest one : with latest version of the code, I never found a way to make the rebuilt UI image call the API one correctly, seems like the URLs are not well-formed… Still investigating.

If you have some news I'll be interested too. jhonygo
410118321 edit docker-compose.yml file add environment can fix the issues 
```
hygieia-ui:
  image: hygieia-ui:latest
  container_name: hygieia-ui
  environment:
    - API_HOST=hygieia-api
    - API_PORT=xxxx
  links:
    - hygieia-api
``` devttao
410225392 Hello,

This is the configuration which works on windows with the existing docker images, yes. But these images are 2+ years old. 

Thus, I tried to rebuild a fresh UI version to get latest patches and this setup doed not seems to work in my company.

Did someone experienced to rebuild and run the latest code on docker for windows? jhonygo

425794090 You can use this API to get which custom_field belongs to which value : 

https://yourjira.com/rest/api/2/issue/<Your issue Id>?expand=names 

Example : 

https://myjira.net/rest/api/2/issue/RAD-737?expand=names

Just add `?expand=names` in the end of your issues, you will get your custom filed mapping details. shardulsrivastava

column2:
I was getting JavaScript syntax errors when using the db-setup.js through piping it in the db-setup.sh shell script. I believe the reason is that the mongo interactive shell and the script execution use different interpreters, as described in the below documentation.

https://docs.mongodb.com/manual/tutorial/write-scripts-for-the-mongo-shell/#differences-between-interactive-and-scripted-mongo

Using the JavaScript equivalent for `use <database>` and executing the script instead of piping it seems to solve the aforementioned issue.

column5: Artifactory collector Error
column11:
405607519 @stangem : This looks like and SSLHandshakeException.

1. Obtain the certificate from the target server: "https://www.artifacts.company.com".
You could do this by contacting somebody or just putting that URL on your browser and clicking on the  "Not Secure" or the Lock sign in front of the URL on the browser, and download the certificate.

2. Now you need to add this to your JVM trust store:
$JAVA_HOME/jre/lib/security/ for JREs or $JAVA_HOME/lib/security for JDKs, there is file called cacerts.

3. Import the new cert use the below command:
keytool -import -file {the certificate file} -alias {some meaningful name} -keystore {path to cacerts file}

Hope this helps. Thanks. subodhbattina
405917970 Awesome that fixed the error, Thank you! stangem

column2: We have deployed Hygieia over Openshift but we have detected a problem. Each time the Mongodb container is redeployed, the data structure is regenerated in such a way that previously saved data is lost, even if the /data/db folder has been associated with a volume. Could it be that the image of Mongodb is ephemeral? What are we doing wrong? Can someone help us? Thanks in advance.
column5: Problems in Openshift to maintain data in Mongodb after redeployment
column11:
404620861 At least in our case, we take a backup and then restore it during the deployment process. Sbrenthughes
404753294 Thanks, although finally we have decided to deploy a new Mongodb service alternatively to Hygieia's one and bind it to a volume to get persistence. Successfully it works. So we don't need to take backup before deploy and restore it after, only in a normal way to preserve data in case server is broken down. gars01

column5: Debug API
column11:
403504761 @matthiasthomas We use IntelliJ here, but basically you will have to start your api in debug mode instead of run, and then after that basically put your break points, and hit the api if you know the parameters directly via your browser or just navigate the application to hit the api. subodhbattina
403589868 Hi @subodhbattina ! Thanks for your answer.
I'm not sure what command line I should use in the debugging configuration though. I installed intellij and imported the project just to see if that changed anything but it doesn't. Could you check what's the configuration you're using to debug it ?
I haven't been able to run it from the IDE either btw, I usually just run the jar from the console using "java -jar api.jar ...", but my knowledge of Java/Maven is pretty limited. matthiasthomas
403864637 @matthiasthomas : 

1. On the top right-hand corner of IntelliJ (where there is a play and debug) buttons, where it says "Application", click on the arrow to show the drop down, and click on "Edit Configuration"

2. On the next screen that appears, on the top left corner, there is "plus" button, click on it and select "JAR Application".

3. And then provide:
3.1 Name, 
3.2 Path to JAR
3.3 VM options (-D options), and then 
3.4 In the "Program arguments", provide a path to your "application.properties" file.
3.5 Select your JRE, and click OK.

And then go back to top right corner of the IDE, select your JAR configuration name, and click on "debug" icon. Hope this helps, let me know if you have any more questions.


 subodhbattina

column2:
Currently I have requirement to fetch all the issues related to particular board. Currently we have that option on Jira widget to select team & this field corresponds to "**jiraTeamFieldName**" field present in each issues
But my concern is what if a Jira issue is found on many boards, also I don't think mapping between board and issue is handled at issue end?
Thus please help me understand the structure if my understanding is wrong
column5: Jira Api: How issues are linked to particular boards are fetched?
column11:
402205790 @ArjunSreepad : From the Jira Collector standpoint, when it pulls down issues, if the JSON response has the same issue listed "separately", mapped to two different teams, then it will get stored separately in the data base mapped out to the two different teams. The "feature" collection has a property called "sTeamID" thats maps the issue to a team.

The way the collector stands as-of-now, it does not parse multiple team names on the response. It expects a single team name, which is what it maps the issue to. subodhbattina
402220952 which field in the issue's response json holds the team details? arjunsreepad
402742616 @ArjunSreepad : Last time I worked on it I saw it coming on the field "customfield_11248".
Example below.
"customfield_11248": {
                    "self": "https://{jira-host-name}/rest/api/2/customFieldOption/10895",
                    "value": {TeamName},
                    "id": "10895"
                },

This is the same field you would set in your "application.properties" file when you run your JIRA collector.
```feature.jiraTeamFieldName=customfield_11248```

When you get story information using the API below: You will have to change your query params based on your needs. On the JSON response, there is a section **"names": {}**.
This contains all the field names. In that list, search for "Team", and I think this is the first field that comes up: **"customfield_11248": "Team"**

```https://{Jira-host-name}/rest/api/latest/search?jql=updatedDate%3E%3D'2016-03-01+00:00'+AND+issueType+IN+('Story')+ORDER+BY+updated+ASC&expand=schema,names&fields=*all,-comment,-watches,-worklog,-votes,-reporter,-creator,-attachment&maxResults=100&startAt=0``` subodhbattina
403855668 @ArjunSreepad : Since we didn't hear back from you, assuming this issue is closed at your end. Closing this issue. Thanks subodhbattina

column2:
Hi,

We are running Github collector against Enterprise Github and we have a 5 mins cron. We have around 100 dashboards(repos) on bordered and it will be thousands of dashboards(repos) in the future. Enterprise Github reported that there are huge API calls due to collector. We would like to optimize the code. Appreciate your suggestions.

Thanks,
Booma Baskaran.
column5: How to reduce API calls in Github collector
column11:
400701433 @Booma-Baskaran : We are working on a webhook (event push based) solution and will update you shortly. Currently work is in progress and we are working on solving the security issues around it. You should hear back in couple of weeks. rvema
400703755 @rvema Thanks for the update. Booma-Baskaran
401085260 @Booma-Baskaran - also make sure you are using the graphql version of the github collector matthewbeasley
401311930 @matthewbeasley Thanks Booma-Baskaran

column5: GitHub Blocked in the Organization any alternative
column11:
400661470 Hi ..my organization has a strict policy and has blocked GitHub .We have got one time permission to get the Hygieia software alone downloaded ..however the Bower and package json has tons of packages that needs to be installed from GitHub and looks like that's not an option ..is there a possibility to get the Hygieia installed and running in any alternate method ? Phoenix9032
401075910 @Phoenix9032 - download and build Hygieia from outside your organizations network. Then move the completed artifacts. For the UI, tar up the dist folder. For the java application just move the jars. We currently don't have up-to-date build artifacts available.  matthewbeasley
401088714 That is really helpful suggestion ..thanks so much ..I will try and if some guidance need d might open up another thread  Phoenix9032

column2:
### Quick resume
Replace DefaultLdapAuthoritiesPopulator by NullLdapAuthoritiesPopulator in order to:

- Avoid unnecessary LDAP Request
- Avoid `[LDAP: error code 32 - No Such Object]` in some case (#1439)

### In details

By default, Spring Security used DefaultLdapAuthoritiesPopulator in order to collect user's groups from LDAP.

If I understand well, **admin** role in Hygieia is assigned by the database and can not be assigned using LDAP groups (no parameter to configure Groups search in the LDAP and authorities retrieved using mongo database).

Due to DefaultLdapAuthoritiesPopulator, Spring Security does a LDAP request after login to get user's groups. I have replaced it by NullLdapAuthoritiesPopulator in order to remove this unnecessary request to LDAP.

Furthermore this can cause some LDAP errors regarding to the configuration of the server: `[LDAP: error code 32 - No Such Object]` (same problem than #1439)
column5: Avoid Spring Security to query user's groups from LDAP

Is there any collector available for pulling custom XML or HTML test reports from a remote server(or jenkins) and display it to the hygieia dashboard.

Preferably if the XML format complies to certain format(like the one generated in JUnit). My requirement is to have get  custom XML test reports that are available in jenkins server(not as a cucumber report) to show it in hygieia dashboard. Currently one option for Junit test results is to upload them to SonarQube and get it. But some of my tests are not based on Junit and are created as custom XML format. How do i achieve it?

column2:
The renameDashboard API pulls all existing dashboards and then searches each one for a dashboard with the same title. The causes performance issues when there are a high number of dashboards.

Changes include:
Removed search logic and added logic to directly check the db for dashboards with an existing title.
Also, added null check

401539540 I know the UI for configuring SCM collectors parses strings in a weird way. I had to attempt a configuration and view the collector log to see if the path to the repo was correct, then tweak the config to the the path I needed.

For BitBucket it looked like: https://bitbucket.path.com/[PROJECT]/[REPO] (No / at end).

For GitHub it looked like: https://github.com/[PRIVATEORG]/[REPO] (No / at end).
From Log: https://api.github.com/repos/[PRIVATEORG]/[REPO]/pulls?[QUERY] (This works, you can validate in your browser).

Then just put you branch name in the branch field. If you use feature/ or anything/ for your development branch management, Hygieia can not parse it properly and will fail. georgehipp
401857915 @georgehipp Thanks for looking into it, George. You are right about the Hygieia UI treating URL strings differently- I had to use the project ID in the URL instead of the Path/workspace/projectname to make it work.  jyotimittal01

column2: There is no rest service expose for getting git server on Oracle Developer Cloud Service, only command line. In this case, how to create collector for git server on Oracle Developer Cloud Service?
column5: How to create collector for git server on Oracle Developer Cloud Service?
column11:
398766408 @yuhong02 The github collector should work fine as long as there is connectivity between the collector instance and your git server on Oracle Developer cloud.  rvema
401078072 @yuhong02 - please follow @rvema suggestion. If it does not work for you please follow this guide http://capitalone.github.io/Hygieia/create_collector.html to create a custom collector.  matthewbeasley
401275636 thanks. yuhong02

Thanks.

column2:
Hi Team,
I checked out the latest code today from master branch and after installing the mongodb and creating the dashboarduser in mongodb using the mongo client, I tried running the api.jar and collectors but I am getting the below error during the start up of the jar files:

org.mongodb.driver.cluster - No server chosen by PrimaryServerSelector from cluster description ClusterDescription{type=UNKNOWN, connectionMode=SINGLE, all=[ServerDescription{address=localhost:27017, type=UNKNOWN, state=CONNECTING, exception={com.mongodb.MongoSocketOpenException: Exception opening socket}, caused by {java.net.ConnectException: Connection refused (Connection refused)}}]}. Waiting for 30000 ms before timing out
Caused by: com.mongodb.MongoTimeoutException: Timed out after 30000 ms while waiting for a server that matches PrimaryServerSelector. Client view of cluster state is {type=UNKNOWN, servers=[{address=localhost:27017, type=UNKNOWN, state=CONNECTING, exception={com.mongodb.MongoSocketOpenException: Exception opening socket}, caused by {java.net.ConnectException: Connection refused (Connection refused)}}]

I am running the mongodb, the collector and the api on the same VM, while the mongo client installed on the VM is successfully able to connect to the db, the connection is failing from within the application code. Please let me know if this is a known issue and if there is a workaround.

column2:
Hi There,

Since we are using Hygieia as single consolidate dashboard for different project development tools, and it really help us in that, now we are started using couple of other tools in our project like:

- veracode for security scanning
- drone as CI/CD tool
- VSTS, story tracker like Jira

I don't see supported collectors for above mentioned, can Hygieia support these tools as well. Please update me on this, if so.

Thx.

So `jiraSprintDataFieldName ` should be `customfield_10101`.
- `"customfield_10102":"SCRUM-5"` represents `Epic` for `SCRUM-5` is epic. So `jiraEpicIdFieldName` should be `customfield_10102`.
- `"customfield_10106":1` represents `Story Points`. So `jiraStoryPointsFieldName` should be `customfield_10106`.

Am I right? Prodesire
397511869 Well, after serval times trying, I solved the problem.

1. `feature.jiraIssueTypeName` should be `feature.jiraIssueTypeNames`. I missed `s`
2. The value of `feature.jiraIssueTypeNames` can't be `故事`, otherwise JIRA can't find this issue type. Actually, we should assign `Story` to `feature.jiraIssueTypeNames` what ever language you set in JIRA.

Now, when running `jira collector`, we could see these logs:

401010230 Hi,
  how do you solve this issue? han2013
401011233 @matthewbeasley my logs showing no errors,but no data showing on UI.Thanks for your help. han2013
419626266 I think we can break such issues into two part:
1. Jira collector collecting feature data in mongo db
2. UI not displaying the data on component.

In my case data is present in the feature collection that means issue is not jira collector and i can browse through the data in mongo database, so Jira collector is working fine. But what if UI still does not display data. I tried looking at requests going from UI in the developer db. But still son't see data on UI looks like it sends request to the UI port 3000 instead of API server running on the 8080 port. I am just wondering if i can see what it means to server.
[http://localhost:3000/api/iteration?agileType=kanban&component=5b911909f4552a1ea47b8220&projectId=43225&teamId=19508](url) 

I can see the list of projects and teams in the jira component and looks like it is selecting these ids based on selected ui elements. 
Does it even connects to server at all(I hope not connecting directly to DB)? If yes then how to trace back to the database. I am wondering if it is UI issue since i can't see any logs progressing on server for this request.
 Sandeep-Mandori
419648593 Tested above link 
[http://localhost:3000/api/iteration?agileType=kanban&component=5b911909f4552a1ea47b8220&projectId=43225&teamId=19508](url)

This looks in the feature collection and values going from the team collection i.e. the values which i select while configuring the feature widget . i.e. Project name and Team name from the widget. Now issue is TeamId mismatch inbetween team and feature collection. In feature collection i don't have teamId=19508 which is populated by the jira collector whereas my team collection has 19508 for the selected team. I am not sure from where team collection is populated and how i can fix this. Since both ids are different it does not display any data. I am not sure what configuration can fix this issue. Sandeep-Mandori

column11:
396775183 Didn't work, but thanks for contribution. japm94
396780446 Okay so you did get data. On the repo you are collecting from, with was the last commit? Also, do you have data in the `commits` Document in your db? Sbrenthughes
396908525 I think so, when I execute `db.commits.find().pretty()` on mongo, returns the commits. japm94
396961024 @japm94  Commits with in last 15 days ? nireeshT
397476270 Guys, I solution the problem. Phabricator API return date in milliseconds, then I just multiplied by 1000. Thank you to who spent your time with me! japm94
396670591 We need to see logs from the github collector as well as your properties file.  Sbrenthughes
396712147 ![screen shot 2018-06-12 at 16 28 35](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/11621060/41312543-b08f8750-6e5d-11e8-8450-1c2c8fe4dd5c.png)

The collector it is working fine.

application.properties
# Database Name
dbname=dashboarddb

# Database HostName - default is localhost
dbhost=localhost

# Database Port - default is 27017
dbport=27017

# Database Password - default is blank
dbpassword=dbpassword

# Logging File location
logging.file=./logs/phabricator.log

# Collector schedule (required)
git.cron=0 * * * * *

# Mandatory parameters
git.host=myhost.com

#Phabricator API TOKEN
git.apiToken=xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx

# Maximum number of days to go back in time when fetching commits
git.commitThresholdDays=15

# Page size for rest calls
git.pageSize=25 japm94
396719498 Not sure if it’s related, but I had a similar problem on the Jenkins code quality collector where I had to add 3 more things to the collector, instanceUrl, jobname and joburl ( not correct casing) see https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/blob/master/collectors/build/jenkins-codequality/src/main/java/com/capitalone/dashboard/collector/JenkinsCodeQualityCollector.java

You may not have this issue with your collector... but it’s worth a check.

I’ve assumed you’ve written your own collector rather than use the hygieia one. Again may not be true! stevegal
396775183 Didn't work, but thanks for contribution. japm94

column11:
396388841 @NeomiS1993  use property key - sonar.metrics[0] instead nireeshT
396537983 @nireeshT Thanks it worked. I was working on Hygieia-2.0.4 release, in this version metrics field is a String. I have seen the new updates in Hygieia master , metrics is now List<String> and updations for sonar versions more than 6.x . I have updated with new code  and changed the property file , sonar.metrics to sonar.metrics[0]. Now its working fine. NeomiS1993

column2:
It would be nice if we could have a cloudwatch log collector and chart the results. 

We could pull the data from cloudwatch using a filter to collect the log data and count the number of entries in the query in the last collection period. This would give people the ability to perform some log monitoring live on the collected logs. For example, if I had a log entry like `{"eventName":"myEvent"}` the gets logged for each interaction with my service, I could query for them in the collector by getting logs with a defined filter-pattern (in this case `{$.eventName="myEvent"}`) and just counting the number in the collection period that match the filter pattern.

We could then chart them.

I guess the configuration would be something like
```properties
aws.cloudwatch.filters[0].name=mySeries1
aws.cloudwatch.filters[0].filter={$.eventName="myEvent"}

aws.cloudwatch.filters[1].name=mySeries2
aws.cloudwatch.filters[1].filter={$.eventName="myEvent2"}
```

Not sure it we could target different graphs type etc... but that might be too far.

This would give a live insight into the logs without needing to drop to the aws cloudwatch console and would also give insight into usage through time.

Using Java 1.8 on a Mac, I cannot build api-audit. The model package contains a
‘’’
    public Map<AuditType, Evaluator> evaluatorMap() {
        return Collections.unmodifiableMap(Stream.of(
                new SimpleEntry<>(AuditType.CODE_REVIEW, codeReviewEvaluator),
                new SimpleEntry<>(AuditType.CODE_QUALITY, codeQualityEvaluator),
                new SimpleEntry<>(AuditType.STATIC_SECURITY_ANALYSIS, staticSecurityAnalysisEvaluator),
                new SimpleEntry<>(AuditType.LIBRARY_POLICY, libraryPolicyEvaluator),
                new SimpleEntry<>(AuditType.BUILD_REVIEW, buildEvaluator),
                new SimpleEntry<>(AuditType.TEST_RESULT, regressionTestResultEvaluator),
                new SimpleEntry<>(AuditType.PERF_TEST, performanceTestResultEvaluator))
                .collect(Collectors.toMap(SimpleEntry::getKey, SimpleEntry::getValue)));
    }’’’
That is causing a generics issue. If you use a more simple map, it build fine.

395213818 @stevegal - which map have you tried? matthewbeasley
395218589 It's not a problem with the map itself. Generics in Java are type erased at runtime as I'm sure you know. I did a build on my mac with `mvn clean install` and got a `incompatible types: inference variable V has incompatible bounds
    equality constraints: com.capitalone.dashboard.evaluator.Evaluator
    lower bounds: ? extends com.capitalone.dashboard.evaluator.Evaluator<? extends com.capitalone.dashboard.response.AuditReviewResponse<? extends java.lang.Enum<? extends java.lang.Enum<?>>>>,U`

when it is building `src/main/java/com/capitalone/dashboard/model/DashboardAuditModel.java:[54,43] ` in that module. 

Obviously it works in the linux build in Travis, and once built I'm sure the bytecode works. 
However if you either cast each typed evaluator to the base evaulator (eg... `new SimpleEntry<>(AuditType.CODE_REVIEW, (Evaluator)codeReviewEvaluator)`) then it will all work. 

However, I personally dislike using streams in this way as its not the simplest thing that works. If you have a fixed map, then build it without the stream complication.

 stevegal
395220320 I've done a PR (https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/pull/2266) with the type 1 fix,
and an alternative one with the (imho) simpler straight map version (https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/pull/2267) stevegal

We are using JIRA (Cloud) and not using any teams. Will this JIRA collector work without teams? I am not able to get anything to show up.

When selecting the widget in the UI you have to select a team (but none show for our setup).

The documentation references:
> If your JIRA instance uses Boards as Teams (instead of the Teams plugin), then set feature.jiraBoardAsTeam property to true.

So does this imply that false really does turn it off completely? I have the properties set to false now.

Documentation also references:
> Check the JIRA URL to see if you are getting any team data in response. Example JIRA URL: https://your-jira-base-url/rest/agile/1.0/board?startAt=0.

Using the above api call - I do get a 50 out of 135 results, but nothing references "team".

I'm facing with a problem: 
  We had used the jenkins pipeline job to deploy our apps for a while, and these days I was trying to add the 
snippets generated by `Hygieia-Jenkins Plugin` to the pipeline code, and I was able to pubilsh the deploy steps to Hygieia Dashboard, however, the dashboard was red, and the deploy order wasn't right ether, see below:
 - jenkins pipeline steps
  ![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/20741596/40772554-dccc9e62-64f2-11e8-8c05-cb180ef86c15.png)

- Hygieia dashboard widget
  ![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/20741596/40772616-0acabfba-64f3-11e8-8e0a-3f3e4fac3e59.png)

Please help.

And there is an other question, as it is described here [Hygieia-Jenkins Plugin](https://capitalone.github.io/Hygieia/hygieia-jenkins-plugin.html), the `mvn clean package` will generate to files: `hygieia-publisher.hpi` and `hygieia-publisher.jar`, so, what's the use of `hygieia-publisher.jar`?  Or should it be used and how can I use it ?


Best regards & thanks a lot.
column5: The deploy order published by Hygieia-Jenkins Plugin doesn't right
column11:
393470702 Does anyone meet this before ? Any help would be great appreciation. ykfq
393498997 I hava figured out why the widget is red.
The `hygieiaDeployPublishStep: Hygieia Deployment Publish Step` has many build status, when the deployment is success, we should publish `Success` from jenkins pipeline to hygieia.  
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/20741596/40779475-ba5c354e-6507-11e8-87be-04543aefc429.png)
 ykfq
393499595 But is the order a problem ?  I've found that the screenshots of official is also disorderd
see [here](https://capitalone.github.io/Hygieia/media/images/Screenshots/hygiea-screenshot.jpg) ykfq
398197917 It would probably be nice to have some sort of order there.  I am going to close the issue since you seem to have it resolved.  Sbrenthughes

column2:
Hi,
We have ldap authentication active on our Jenkins install (not using Jenkins local user db).
I'm trying to configure the jenkins build collector but it always fails with:

```
2018-05-28 10:30:00,225 INFO  c.c.d.collector.CollectorTask - Error getting jobs for: http://our.jenkins.server.tld:8080/ 0s
2018-05-28 10:30:00,228 ERROR c.c.d.collector.DefaultHudsonClient - client exception loading jobs
org.springframework.web.client.HttpClientErrorException: 401 Invalid password/token for user: myuser
```

Though, I can see all jobs when configuring the build widget.

The application.properties file:

```
dbname=dashboarddb
dbhost=localhost
dbport=27017
dbreplicaset=false
dbhostport=localhost:27017,127.0.0.1:27017,ip-10-100-9-120:27017
dbusername=dbuser
dbpassword=password
jenkins.cron=0 0/5 * * * *
jenkins.pageSize=1000
jenkins.folderDepth=10
jenkins.servers[0]=http://our.jenkins.server.tld:8080/
jenkins.usernames[0]=myuser
jenkins.apiKeys[0]=b344df0bfd19352f2a2cf4046eaa1745
jenkins.saveLog=false
jenkins.searchFields[0]= options.jobName
jenkins.searchFields[1]= niceName
```

Is it not possible to use an ldap accout with a token?

Thank you
Tomas
column5: Jenkis Build Collector with ldap user and token fails
column11:
392595776 @xhostAB can you try this way 
jenkins.servers[0]=http://myuser:b344df0bfd19352f2a2cf4046eaa1745@our.jenkins.server.tld:8080/

remove 
jenkins.usernames[0]=myuser
jenkins.apiKeys[0]=b344df0bfd19352f2a2cf4046eaa1745

how you got this apiKey - b344df0bfd19352f2a2cf4046eaa1745 ? nireeshT
392665792 @nireeshT thanks did try that too (forgot to mention), but I got it working after I added the jenkins url and account in the dashboard under Admin -> General Configuration -> Hudson
Not sure why there are two settings? application.properties and in the dashboard? xhostAB
392783943 We are working to move away from properties files as much as possible. Hopefully, in the near future, Hygieia would only need to know the db credentials via properties file or some other method. The rest of the properties would be stored in the database.  Sbrenthughes

column2:
## Summary

Build failure due to inability to download tarball.

**Update**: The URL is for `http`, when npm switched to `https`, and the plug-in (`eirslett/frontend-maven-plugin`) doesn't seem to support redirects from http to https.

## Configuration

* Ubuntu 14.04 Trusty Tahr (clean)
* Java 1.8.0_171-b11
* Maven 3.3.9

## Steps

1. Install Oracle Java 1.8.0
2. Install Maven - `apt-get install maven`
3. cd /path/to/hygieia
4. `mvn clean install package`

## Expected Results

As per instructions, expected it to not error: http://capitalone.github.io/Hygieia/setup.html.

This error seems to be related to downloading using: `http://registry.npmjs.org/npm/-/npm-5.0.1.tgz`.  The mechanism to download this is not working.

## Actual Results

```
INFO] ------------------------------------------------------------------------
[INFO] BUILD FAILURE
[INFO] ------------------------------------------------------------------------
[INFO] Total time: 16:33 min
[INFO] Finished at: 2018-05-28T01:40:52+00:00
[INFO] Final Memory: 121M/241M
[INFO] ------------------------------------------------------------------------
[ERROR] Failed to execute goal com.github.eirslett:frontend-maven-plugin:0.0.29:install-node-and-npm (install node and npm) on project UI: Could not download npm: Could not download http://registry.npmjs.org/npm/-/npm-5.0.1.tgz: Unknown host registry.npmjs.org: Name or service not known -> [Help 1]
[ERROR]
[ERROR] To see the full stack trace of the errors, re-run Maven with the -e switch.
[ERROR] Re-run Maven using the -X switch to enable full debug logging.
[ERROR]
[ERROR] For more information about the errors and possible solutions, please read the following articles:
[ERROR] [Help 1] http://cwiki.apache.org/confluence/display/MAVEN/MojoFailureException
[ERROR]
[ERROR] After correcting the problems, you can resume the build with the command
[ERROR]   mvn <goals> -rf :UI
```
## NOTES

When I curl manually, I noticed a 301:

```
HTTP/1.1 301 Moved Permanently
Date: Mon, 28 May 2018 01:53:03 GMT
Transfer-Encoding: chunked
Connection: keep-alive
Cache-Control: max-age=3600
Expires: Mon, 28 May 2018 02:53:03 GMT
Location: https://registry.npmjs.org/npm/-/npm-5.0.1.tgz
Server: cloudflare

column2:
## Summary

Build failure due to module not compatible with system Maven.  The documentation does not specify any version of Maven so I used the default.  Might want to make this clear in the docs, little to nothing on requirements.

## Configuration

* Ubuntu 14.04 Trusty Tahr (clean)
* Java 1.8.0_171-b11

## Steps

1. Install Oracle Java 1.8.0
2. Install Maven - `apt-get install maven`
3. cd /path/to/hygieia
4. `mvn clean install package`

## Expected Results

As per instructions, expected it to not error: http://capitalone.github.io/Hygieia/setup.html

If a particular version of Java and/or Maven are required, then expected this would be documented in setup.

## Actual Results

column5: adding updated sonar interface to fetch for Sonar 5.6.7 with more than 500 projects

column2:
As of Sonar 6.2 the /api/resource sonar qube is removed. There's various limits on this (500 projects fetch etc.) in previous versions (could only test with 5.6.7).

Proper channel would be to fetch via /api/projects.
See my example PR. It's a simple fix, but didn't go to far in modifying existing logic.

column2:
During the initial build of the project (with a fresh maven install), the build failed on the core module.  I corrected the issue by updating the core pom.xml file to include:
        <dependency>
            <groupId>org.springframework</groupId>
            <artifactId>spring-web</artifactId>
        </dependency>
column5: Initial build failed
column11:
391009743 @Neumsy - could you provide more information about the specific failure that occurred and what you did to fix it? matthewbeasley
391060043 I received an error message running mvn install on the project that it could not find some of the spring http classes on the core module.  To resolve the issue, I added a dependency to the spring-web module in the core/pom.xml file.  

This may be due to the spring-web being a transitive dependency and we are behind a corporate firewall with an internal Maven/Artifactory repository.  Adding the dependency loaded it into our internal repository which now works correctly on a new build.

Unfortunately since I resolved the issue, I cannot duplicate the error message I saw.  But this is what I added to the pom.xml file:

```
<dependency>
            <groupId>org.springframework</groupId>
            <artifactId>spring-web</artifactId>
</dependency>
``` Neumsy

column2:
I am trying to collect data from SonarQube hosted server v6.7.1. I provided properties file as described here: http://capitalone.github.io/Hygieia/sonar.html but there's no clue about how to authenticate on the Sonar server. Our server requires auth to read any data.

I tried to generate api token and provide `sonar.servers[0]` as `https://api-token@sonar-server` or  `https://sonar-user:api-token@sonar-server` with no use:

`c.c.d.collector.DefaultSonar6Client - org.springframework.web.client.HttpClientErrorException: 401`

Curl, wget and powershell webrequests are all reporting status 200 with URL `https://api-token@sonar-server`. I examined `SonarCollector.java` in Hygieia project but found nothing except servers, versions, and metrics. 

Is there any way to authenticate the collector on a sonar server?
column5: Sonar collector authentication
column11:
391745378 Checking out the sonar collector settings(via the code) I was able to see that you should be able to do the following:
` sonar.username= `
    `sonar.password=` Sbrenthughes

column2:
Hello Everyone,

I had success in reading Commit Stage on Product Dashboard but had no luck on populating Build Stage. 
Options tried 
1.  DefaultPipeline  ( dont recall- why it wasnt showing data)
2. DynamicPipeline  (Issue: it is looking data in CodeRepos collection in creating BuildPipelineResponse and I didnt find any code that writes codeRepos from Bamboo Build Collector , where as codeRepos are being populated in Jenkins Build Collector ) -- GetBuildDetails method

I understand that the recommended way is to use Hygieia Publisher to push data into Hygieia 

Here is Collectors information 
1. Bitbucket Collector
2. Bamboo Build Collector
3. Custom Bamboo Deploy Collector

Question I have for you all out there is ?
Is Product Dashboard Pipeline has worked with Pull Strategy (using Collectors) to display data from Bitbucket, Bamboo Build

What is the recommended approach should I use Default Pipeline or DyanmicPipeline for Pull Strategy with Collectors and not using Publisher ? I am guessing it should be DynamicPipeline
column5: Product Dashboard

column11: 391725291 @trinathtiru Are you sure your mongodb is running correctly? and the login credentials for MongoDB are correctly mentioned in the application properties . Per the above conversation, I believe you are using the below command to bring up your application? `java -jar github-collector.jar --spring.config.name=github --spring.config.location=/usr/Hygieia/collectors/scm/github/application.properties` rvema 392273620 @trinathtiru @Phoenix9032 looks like there is lot of confusion going around with github.key and github.personalAccessToken github.key is value generated from core module. You can generate this key from UI as admin user. 1) create an admin user - useername - "admin" , password -"you can chose any password" 2) go to admin settings -> Generate Api token -> create new key by setting name and expiration date. 3) Copy the generated key to github properties file as github.key = "generated key". 4) Go to api.properties file, add property -> key = "generated key" 5) Generated key is used to encrypt password when you configure github repository for accessing private repos. column2:
I have a private repo on Bitbucket server (stash). I configured everything as described here: http://capitalone.github.io/Hygieia/setup.html#encryption-for-private-repos but still got 401 error, so I decided to investigate the case before posting a new issue.

I've added `LOG.debug("decryptedPassword: " + decryptedPassword);` to `DefaultBitbucketServerClient.java` and here's what I've seen in the log: 

```
DEBUG c.c.d.c.DefaultBitbucketServerClient - decryptedPassword: rd
```

Guess what? My password is `rd#SomeOtherSymbolsAndDigits`. Looks like the hashtag symbol `#` ruins the decryption process. Therefore I am forced to change password or use other credentials with no `#` in the password string.

Any suggestions how to fix this? I am not a java programmer so I can't fix it myself and I really don't want to change password on a technical login.
column5: Bitbucket collector -- decryptedPassword issue
column11: 389966550 Encryption and Decryption is handle via a Java library. Hygieia doesn't manage this.  Sbrenthughes

column2: When you do a "mvn clean" in the UI directory, it ought to remove dist, node, node_modules and bower_components.  Otherwise, it's not really clean.
column5: maven clean should remove dist, node, node_modules and bower_components
column11: 392904429 @panglin - we use https://github.com/eirslett/frontend-maven-plugin for the UI portion of the build. According to the developer it's "Not meant to install Node for production uses. The Node usage is intended as part of a frontend build, running common javascript tasks such as minification, obfuscation, compression, packaging, testing etc." That being said, if you have issues with the way this plugin works you should file an issue on their github page. matthewbeasley

Hi All,
We are facing an issue wherein the dashboarduser thats created in mongodb gets deleted after a gap of 2-3 weeks causing the dashboard to disappear. This has been a recurring issue for us, all collectors, api, UI and mongodb are running on the same machine. Below are the db properties that we have been using in collectors and API:
dbname=dashboarddb
dbhost=localhost
dbport=27017
dbusername=dashboarduser
dbpassword=dbpassword

Once the dashboard is gone, I have to create the dashboarduser again in mongodb and then re-create the dashboards from scratch.
Please let me know if anyone else has faced a similar issue.
column5: dashboarduser gets deleted from mongodb
column11:
389756731 Check logs. Check logins, check history, etc. a db drop has nothing to do with the application. Maybe there is an exploit and some does plays with you?  cradules
389905891 @DeepakYadav17  No cleanup logic in code. Check if you recreate Mongo on server rehydration, that is one way I could think of.  nireeshT
390556181 Thanks for the responses @cradules and @nireeshT , I will check and will get back on this. DeepakYadav17
391852661 @DeepakYadav17 it would be nice to know how you installed mongodb on your localhost. If you are using docker for instance then it could be that you aren't mapping a data volume in which case the data will be lost upon container restart.  matthewbeasley
